"Perez T., Garrabou J., Sartoretto S., Harmelin J.-G., Francour P., Vacelet J.","Mass mortality of marine invertebrates: An unprecedented event in the Northwestern Mediterranean",2000,"Comptes Rendus de l'Academie des Sciences - Serie III","323","10",,"853","865",,,10.1016/S0764-4469(00)01237-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033623676&partnerID=40&md5=8efabd081e8e82f29d65e1a52d57ddff","Centre d'Océanologie De Marseille, UMR 6540 Dimar, Station Marine d'Endoume, rue de la Batterie-des-Lions, 13007 Marseille, France; Laboratoire d'Environnement Marin Littoral, Faculté Des Sciences, Université De Nice-Sophia-Antipolis, 06108 Nice cedex 2, France","Perez, T., Centre d'Océanologie De Marseille, UMR 6540 Dimar, Station Marine d'Endoume, rue de la Batterie-des-Lions, 13007 Marseille, France; Garrabou, J., Centre d'Océanologie De Marseille, UMR 6540 Dimar, Station Marine d'Endoume, rue de la Batterie-des-Lions, 13007 Marseille, France; Sartoretto, S., Centre d'Océanologie De Marseille, UMR 6540 Dimar, Station Marine d'Endoume, rue de la Batterie-des-Lions, 13007 Marseille, France; Harmelin, J.-G., Centre d'Océanologie De Marseille, UMR 6540 Dimar, Station Marine d'Endoume, rue de la Batterie-des-Lions, 13007 Marseille, France; Francour, P., Laboratoire d'Environnement Marin Littoral, Faculté Des Sciences, Université De Nice-Sophia-Antipolis, 06108 Nice cedex 2, France; Vacelet, J., Centre d'Océanologie De Marseille, UMR 6540 Dimar, Station Marine d'Endoume, rue de la Batterie-des-Lions, 13007 Marseille, France","An unprecedented mass mortality event has been observed at the end of the summer 1999 along the coasts of Provence (France) and Ligury (Italy). This event has severely affected a wide array of sessile filter-feeder invertebrates from hard-substratum communities, such as sponges (particularly the keratose sponges Hippospongia and Spongia), cnidarians (particularly the anthozoans Corallium, Paramuricea, Eunicella and Cladocora), bivalves, ascidians and bryozoans. Along the Provence coasts, the outbreak spread from east to west. Exceptionally high and constant temperatures of the whole water column (23-24 °C, for over one month, down to 40 m) could have determined an environmental context favourable to the mass mortality event. Like the thermal anomaly, the mortality is limited in depth. However, we cannot ascertain whether temperature, had a direct effect on organisms or acted in synergy with a latent and/or waterborne agent (microbiological or chemical). Taking into account the global warming context in the NW-Mediterranean, monitoring programs of physical-chemical parameters and vulnerable populations should rapidly be set up. (C) 2000 Academie des sciences/Editions scientifiques et medicales Elsevier SAS.","Anthozoa; Gorgonians; Mass mortality; Mediterranean; Porifera","water; invertebrate; marine environment; mass mortality; article; Ascidiacea; Bryozoa; coelenterate; controlled study; France; geography; greenhouse effect; invertebrate; Italy; marine environment; Mediterranean Sea; mortality; nonhuman; seashore; temperature; animal; environment; mollusc; physiology; sponge (Porifera); Urochordata; Mediterranean Sea; Anthozoa; Ascidiacea; Bivalvia; Bryozoa; Cladocora; Cnidaria; Coelenterata; Corallium; Eunicella; Gorgonacea; Hippospongia; Invertebrata; Paramuricea; Porifera; Spongia; Animals; Bryozoa; Cnidaria; Environment; France; Greenhouse Effect; Invertebrates; Italy; Mediterranean Sea; Mollusca; Mortality; Porifera; Urochordata",,,,,,"Peres, J.M., Picard, J., Nouveau manuel de bionomie benthique de la mer Mediterranee (1964) Rec. Trav. St. mar. Endoume, 31 (47), pp. 5-137; Vacelet, J., La place des Spongiaires dans les systemes trophiques marins (1979), pp. 259-270. , Levi C. Boury-Esnault N. (Eds.). Biologie des spongiaires, Editions du CNRS, ParisComa, R., Gili, J.M., Zabala, M., Riera, T., Feeding and prey capture cycles in the aposymbiotic gorgonian Paramuricea clavata (1994) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Se